05312nam a22009855i 9780691209753DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912097537 a10.1515/97806912097532doi  a(DE-B1597)548930  a(OCoLC)1153457592  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQ175b.L664 1990 7aPHI0040002bisacsh04a5012231 aLongino, Helen E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScience as Social Knowledge :bValues and Objectivity in Scientific Inquiry /cHelen E. Longino. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tCHAPTER ONE. Introduction: Good Science, Bad Science -- tCHAPTER TWO. Methodology, Goals, and Practices -- tCHAPTER THREE. Evidence and Hypothesis -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Values and Objectivity -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Values and Science -- tCHAPTER SIX. Research on Sex Differences -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Explanatory Models in the Biology of Behavior -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Science in Society -- tCHAPTER NINE. Science and Ideology -- tCHAPTER TEN. Conclusion: Social Knowledge -- tWORKS CONSULTED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConventional wisdom has it that the sciences, properly pursued, constitute a pure, value-free method of obtaining knowledge about the natural world. In light of the social and normative dimensions of many scientific debates, Helen Longino finds that general accounts of scientific methodology cannot support this common belief. Focusing on the notion of evidence, the author argues that a methodology powerful enough to account for theories of any scope and depth is incapable of ruling out the influence of social and cultural values in the very structuring of knowledge. The objectivity of scientific inquiry can nevertheless be maintained, she proposes, by understanding scientific inquiry as a social rather than an individual process. Seeking to open a dialogue between methodologists and social critics of the sciences, Longino develops this concept of "contextual empiricism" in an analysis of research programs that have drawn criticism from feminists. Examining theories of human evolution and of prenatal hormonal determination of "gender-role" behavior, of sex differences in cognition, and of sexual orientation, the author shows how assumptions laden with social values affect the description, presentation, and interpretation of data. In particular, Longino argues that research on the hormonal basis of "sex-differentiated behavior" involves assumptions not only about gender relations but also about human action and agency. She concludes with a discussion of the relation between science, values, and ideology, based on the work of Habermas, Foucault, Keller, and Haraway.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSciencexMethodology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aAustralopithecus.  aBenbow.  aDarwinism.  aDjerassi.  aFairweather.  aHomo Erectus.  aJensen.  aLaetoli.  aMeno.  aNature.  aNew England Journal of Medicine.  aPascal.  aScience.  aStimpson, Shapere.  aZahar.  aanimal models.  acontextual values.  aepistemology.  afeminist.  agender Freeman.  agynecentrism.  ahypothesis.  aneuroendocrinology.  aobservation.  apacemaker cells.  apositivism.  ateleology.  atomboyism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691209753zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/c